    <fr:title text="Holder's Inequality">Holder's Inequality</fr:title>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>
Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(S,\Sigma ,\mu )]]></fr:tex> be a measure space and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p,q\in [1,\ \infty ]]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1/p+1/q=1]]></fr:tex>. Then for all measurable real- or complex-valued functions <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>,

<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\lVert  fg \rVert  \leq  \lVert  f \rVert _{p}\lVert  g \rVert _{q}.]]></fr:tex>

If, in addition, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p,q\in (1,\ \infty )]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\in  L^{q}(\mu )]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\in  L^{q}(\mu )]]></fr:tex>, then Holder's inequality becomes an equality if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lVert  f\rVert ^{p}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lVert  g\rVert ^{q}]]></fr:tex> are linearly dependent in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^{1}(\mu )]]></fr:tex>, meaning that there exist real numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a,\,\beta \geq 0]]></fr:tex>, not both of them zero, such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lVert  f\rVert ^{p}=\beta \,\lVert  g\rVert ^{q}]]></fr:tex> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mu ]]></fr:tex>-almost everywhere.
  </html:p>
